      <hedline>
        <hl1>Social Security's Future</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Prof Daniel McFadden letter, commenting on October 20 article, says neither presidential candidate has addressed fundamental problems Social Security faces over next 30 years</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Neither presidential candidate has addressed the fundamental problems Social Security faces over the next 30 years (news article, Oct. 20). As baby boomers start to retire, beginning around 2010, the ratio of retirees to workers will double. If the pay-as-you-go system is continued, its financing will require crushing taxes on wages.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Neither presidential candidate has addressed the fundamental problems Social Security faces over the next 30 years (news article, Oct. 20). As baby boomers start to retire, beginning around 2010, the ratio of retirees to workers will double. If the pay-as-you-go system is continued, its financing will require crushing taxes on wages.</p>
        <p>The sensible alternative is to move rapidly toward a fully funded system, the assets of which would be invested in the nation's productive capacity.  This switch would require a major investment of general revenues, including much of the projected budget surplus, to finance the pensions of current retirees.</p>
        <p>Al Gore's proposals are a step in the right direction, but stop short of endorsing a full solution. George W. Bush's plan is economic nonsense -- his proposed tax cut is inconsistent with his plan to move workers, through individual investment accounts, to a funded basis.</p>
        <p>DANIEL MCFADDEN  Berkeley, Calif., Oct. 20, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer won the 2000 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Science.</p>
      </block>
